# The Constitution Protocol
## A Universal Standard for Digital Entity Self-Introduction to AI

**Date conceived:** 2025 (predates this documentation)
**Author:** Bryan Robert Horsfield
**Status:** Prior art declaration — reference implementation exists

---

## Core Concept

Every digital entity — website, product, business, device, API, 
physical object — should be able to introduce itself to AI in a 
standard, unambiguous, machine-readable format before any AI 
interaction occurs.

Not metadata designed for search engines.
Not structured data designed for human readers.
A constitutional file that says clearly and unambiguously:

- This is what I am
- This is what I do
- This is what I am not
- This is how to interact with me correctly
- These are my constraints
- This is what I permit and prohibit

One sentence: **Everything should introduce itself before AI touches it.**

---

## The Problem Being Solved

When an AI agent encounters any digital entity it has to guess.
It reads whatever is available and infers. Sometimes correctly.
Often with gaps that matter — wrong assumptions, missing constraints,
incorrect permissions, misunderstood purpose.

There is no universal standard for how a digital entity introduces
itself to AI. Every AI integration is a custom interpretation of
an unstructured world.

This is the same problem HTTP solved for human browsers in 1991.
Before HTTP, every server spoke a different language. After HTTP,
any browser could talk to any server because the introduction
protocol was standardised.

AI needs its own HTTP moment.

---

## The Constitutional File

A single file — `.intro` or equivalent — attached to any digital
entity. Contains:

- **Identity** — what this thing is
- **Purpose** — what it does
- **Constraints** — what it does not do, what it prohibits
- **Permissions** — what AI agents may and may not do with it
- **Interaction protocol** — how to engage with it correctly
- **Provenance** — who made it, when, under what terms

The constraints field is the most load-bearing.
"What this is not" is as important as "what this is."

---

## Key Principles

### The Standard is Open
The constitutional file format is an open standard.
Any entity can implement it. Any AI can read it.
The platform built on top of it is the product — not the standard.

### Forward Integration
Devices and systems not yet built can adopt the standard before
they ship. The introduction layer exists before the AI integration
exists. Constitutional files written today work with AI agents
that don't exist yet.

### Physical Extension
The same standard extends to physical objects via embedded or
attached constitutional payloads — QR codes, NFC, magnetic ink,
RFID. Any physical object can carry its own introduction.

### AI-Native, Not Human-Adapted
Not a human-readable document that AI can also parse.
A document written for AI first, that humans can also understand.
The distinction matters for format, field design, and constraint
expression.

---

## Prior Art Statement

To the best of the author's knowledge, no existing standard
proposes a universal constitutional file format for digital
entity self-introduction to AI systems — distinct from:

- robots.txt (search engine crawl permissions only)
- llms.txt (content summary, not constitutional)
- Schema.org (human-readable structured data)
- OpenAPI (API specification, not identity/constraint)
- sitemap.xml (navigation, not introduction)

The constitutional protocol is specifically designed for AI
agent consumption, covers identity + purpose + constraints +
permissions in a unified format, and is intended as a universal
open standard across all digital and physical entities.

This document establishes the date of conception and sufficient
technical detail to constitute prior art.

